i>Aylard</i>, or <i>Elard</i>. The former two names are usually of native English origin, from Old English <i>Æthelheard</i>, composed of the elements <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heard</i> ‘hard, bold’. Alternatively, the surname may be of continental origin, from an ancient Germanic name (see 2 below), which developed in Old French to <i>Alard</i>, and in Middle Dutch to <i>Adelaert</i> and <i>Alaert</i>. The continental names were used in post-Conquest England by Normans and Flemings. Later development of <i>-ard</i> to <i>-ett</i> and <i>-att</i> in surnames means that these personal names may also lie behind some examples of e.g. <b>Allatt</b> and   Hallett  .","French: from the medieval personal name <i>Alard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Adelhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy’. Compare   Allar  ,   Allor  ,   Allord  , and   Allore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellerd","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Allard  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain.","Probably an altered form of German Ellert, a variant of Ehlert."]},{"name":"Ellert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Merwin, Traude.","English: variant of   Allard  .","German: variant of   Ehlert  ."]},{"name":"Allor","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Allard  ."]},{"name":"Hallett","meanings":["English (mainly Somerset and Dorset): variant of <b>Allatt</b>, itself a variant of   Allard  , with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Ellard","meanings":["English: variant of   Allard  ."]},{"name":"Allore","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Allard  ."]},{"name":"Allord","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Allard  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Allard was christened on 28 May 1598, in Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry Allarde, was 33 and his mother, Phillipa Gibbon, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Anne Allard."},"et":{"28 May 1598–":"28. mai 1598–Surnud","1588–1592":"1588–1592","1589–1589":"1589–1589","1591–1593":"1591–1593","1593–Female":"1593–Surnud","1598–Male":"1598–Surnud","1600–Male":"1600–Surnud","1602–1624":"1602–1624","1603–1644":"1603–1644","1623–1674":"1623–1674","1565–1645":"1565–1645","1569–1624":"1569–1624","1593":"1593","1592":"1592","1591":"1591","28 May 1598":"28. mai 1598","1569":"1569","1624":"1624","1602":"1602","1623":"1623","1645":"1645","1644":"1644","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1588":"1588","1565":"1565","1598":"1598","1674":"1674","9 January 1586":"9. jaanuar 1586","1603":"1603","York, Province of Maine, British Colonial America":"York, Province of Maine, British Colonial America","Biddenden, Kent, England":"Biddenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"28 May 1598–":"28. toukokuuta 1598–Kuollut","1588–1592":"1588–1592","1589–1589":"1589–1589","1591–1593":"1591–1593","1593–Female":"1593–Kuollut","1598–Male":"1598–Kuollut","1600–Male":"1600–Kuollut","1602–1624":"1602–1624","1603–1644":"1603–1644","1623–1674":"1623–1674","1565–1645":"1565–1645","1569–1624":"1569–1624","1593":"1593","1592":"1592","1591":"1591","28 May 1598":"28. toukokuuta 1598","1569":"1569","1624":"1624","1602":"1602","1623":"1623","1645":"1645","1644":"1644","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1588":"1588","1565":"1565","1598":"1598","1674":"1674","9 January 1586":"9. tammi